# Way of Pi UI: modular dock shell

Use this when changing **`apps/wayofpi-ui/`** layout, docking, or technical-shell chrome.

## North star

**Product target (Zed-class):** The **center workspace** should behave like **Zed’s panes**: each **pane** is a **tab stack** of **items**, and an item can be a **file buffer**, a **terminal**, or another **tool surface**—**the same tab chrome and split affordances** (`+`, split, zoom), not a separate “real editor” vs “secondary panels” hierarchy. See **Zed**: [Terminal — *Terminal Panel vs Center Terminal*](https://zed.dev/docs/terminal.html) (e.g. **`workspace: new center terminal`** in the center vs docked terminal **panel**), [Introducing Zed’s new panel system](https://zed.dev/blog/new-panel-system) (left / right / bottom **docks** vs workspace content). **Pane splits** are the modular unit (e.g. `pane::SplitRight` / `pane::SplitDown` in Zed’s action model).

**Honest status of `wayofpi-ui` today:** The **main column** is **`WorkspacePane`**: one **Zed-style tab row** per cell (**files ∪ terminal ∪ problems ∪ output ∪ tool log**), backed by **`PanelDockLayout`** v3 (`tabs` + `activeIndex` in **`panelDockLayout.ts`**). **Multi-cell layout:** **`TechnicalWorkspaceGrid`** (up to **3×4**, **nested flex** + **`DockSplitHandle`**, persisted **`rowWeights`/`colWeights`**) mounts one **`WorkspacePane`** per cell—each cell has its own dock state and **`useFileEditor`** when the grid is active; each cell uses **`WorkspaceCellDropSurface`** (edge snap overlay + drop routing). Persistence **`wayofpi.technical.workspaceGrid.v1`** (**`workspaceGridStorage.ts`**): includes **`growWorkspaceGridForEdgeDrop`**, **`applyWorkspaceGridRowResizeDelta`**, **`applyWorkspaceGridColResizeDelta`**. **Cross-cell** **panel tab** DnD (surface + **tab bar** insert) and **edge-drop** expansion (**1×1** / **N×1** / **1×N** outer edges) are **shipped**. Legacy single-pane users may still have **`wayofpi.panelDock`** only—migrated into grid cell 0 on read. This is **much closer** to Zed’s center stack than the old **center editor vs separate strips** split, but it is **not** yet an arbitrary **pane DAG**—that remains **Phase E / Z** (**`docs/WOP_MODULAR_DOCKS_PLAN.md`**).

**Still true:** **Agent chat**, **primary sidebar**, and **docked regions** remain **peers** in the long-term **layout graph**—same persistence and movability rules—not permanent sacred geometry.

## Terminology (product + docs) — **equal chrome** (Zed-class UI)

Zed’s **implementation** still has center **panes** vs edge **docks**; the **Way of Pi web shell** uses **`WOP_UNIFIED_DOCK_BAND_LABEL`** → **Dock** (`dockChrome.ts`) on **`WorkspacePane`** (and **`PanelDockBand`** where it still appears). Do **not** ship a second label (**Pane** vs **Dock**) for the workspace tab row — users read that as two product kinds.

- **Workspace tab stack** (`WorkspacePane`): **`Dock`**-family **`h-9`** tab row, **+** menu, DnD **`PanelTab`** reorder within the stack (**`PANEL_TAB_DND_TYPE`**). Each **grid cell** (or the single **1×1** pane) owns one **`PanelDockLayout`** slice.
- **Single-cell (1×1) technical UI:** App-level **`selectedPath`** + one **`useFileEditor`** feed the lone **`WorkspacePane`**. **Multi-cell grid:** focused cell drives **`selectedPath`** / menus via **`TechnicalWorkspaceCellSnapshot`**; other cells keep local path state.
- Avoid framing **tool** vs **file** tabs as unrelated **kinds**; both belong to the same dock interaction model (**tabs + body**).
- **Layout JSON:** Per-cell docks live in **`workspaceGridStorage.ts`** (**`wayofpi.technical.workspaceGrid.v1`**) when using the grid; **`readPanelDockLayout` / `writePanelDockLayout`** (**`wayofpi.panelDock`**) remain for migration and any code paths that sync cell 0. **`PanelDockLayout`** is v3: **`{ tabs, activeIndex }`** (legacy **`strips`** migrates on read). Chat/sidebar geometry: **`readDockLayout`** (`technicalLayoutStorage.ts`). Legacy **`wayofpi.technical.toolDock`** migrates into **`panelDock`** once then is removed.

## Appearances and dock composition

**Different appearances** (Pi playground / menu-driven profiles and extension stacks) should **use the same modular dock shell** and differ mainly by **which docks are shown by default**, **where they attach**, and **what tabs/tools/files** each strip or sidebar hosts—not by maintaining a separate hard-coded layout tree per profile.

- **Aggregate / pseudo appearances** (e.g. busy “full playground” vs. lean “project-local Pi” with empty `extensions[]` and stack-via-menu) map to **density presets**: more sidebars, strips, and chat affordances vs. fewer default regions; still the same dock primitives and persistence model.
- **Labeled extension appearances** (each menu line that resolves to a concrete `extensions/<name>.ts`—e.g. `minimal`, `pure-focus`, `agent-team`, `cross-agent`, …) should surface as **dock content and optional default layout**, not as one-off chrome that bypasses strips/sidebars.
- **Simple vs technical** (and any future UI modes in the web app) should toggle or swap **dock presets / saved layout slices**, not fork the entire shell component hierarchy.

When adding or wiring an appearance, prefer **versioned layout JSON + dock region config** (see `technicalLayoutStorage`) over JSX that encodes “this profile always looks like this fixed grid.” Canonical Pi menu → extension mapping lives in **`docs/PLAYGROUND.md`** and playground scripts; this rule only requires that the **web shell** express those differences through **modular docks**.

## Visual parity (“equal docks”)

Any region that is **tabs + body** (e.g. main editor column vs. another horizontal dock) should follow the **same structural pattern**: tab row, optional path/breadcrumb or title row where it makes sense, body. Avoid a pattern where one area looks like a full document surface and another looks like a downgrade-only “panel” unless the difference is an intentional, documented product choice.

## Movability (product target)

Design and persist layout so these become possible **without a rewrite**:

- **Horizontal dock bands** (tab strips) can move relative to the editor (e.g. above vs. below the editor stack, or additional instances).
- **Agent / session** can attach to **left**, **right**, or **bottom** (and future edges), not only one hard-coded side.
- **Primary sidebar** (Explorer, etc.) can live on **left or right** (activity bar follows or mirrors as needed).

Prefer **data-driven layout** (saved regions, split sizes, ordering) over JSX that hard-codes a single tree order when adding new features.

## Multiplicity (product target)

Users may want **several** horizontal docks (e.g. side-by-side or stacked rows), each holding **mixed** tabs (files, panels, tools). **Do not** assume exactly two persisted slots forever; avoid names and types that encode “only top and bottom” as a permanent ceiling unless the UI explicitly documents a temporary limitation.

## Drag-and-drop (required parity)

Within each **`WorkspacePane`** tab row, **tool** and **file** **`PanelTab`** entries are **draggable** for **reorder** (Zed-style insert hint). **Payload:** **`application/x-wop-panel-tab`** + **`serializePanelTab`** / **`parsePanelTabJson`** (`panelDockLayout.ts`), **`WorkspacePane.tsx`**. Moves: **`applyPanelTabMove`**. Persist the affected cell’s layout via **`writeWorkspaceGridState`** (grid) or the **`patchWorkspaceCellDock`** path in **`App.tsx`**.

**Shipped (interim):** **Panel tab** DnD **between** grid cells (workspace surface + **tab-bar** insert); **edge** drops that **grow** the grid when the neighbor did not exist (**`growWorkspaceGridForEdgeDrop`**). **Not yet:** arbitrary **split-from-anywhere** graph; **explorer file** drops onto tab bar at a chosen index (polish); a single persisted **pane DAG**—still **Phase E / Z** (**`docs/WOP_MODULAR_DOCKS_PLAN.md`**).

## Splitter pointer parity (`DockSplitHandle`)

**`DockSplitHandle`** reports deltas in **screen space**: **positive `dx`** = pointer moved **right**, **positive `dy`** = moved **down** (`apps/wayofpi-ui/src/components/DockSplitHandle.tsx`).

When wiring **`onDelta`** to widths/heights:

- The **edge under the user’s grip** should move in the **same direction** as the pointer (natural resize — not “inverse” steering).
- **Vertical bar** between a **left** region and a **right** region: dragging **right** moves the boundary **right** → typically **grow the left** / **shrink the right** (apply **`−dx`** to the **right** pane’s stored width if that width is the right column’s size).
- **Horizontal bar** between **upper** and **lower** regions: dragging **down** moves the boundary **down** with the pointer. If the **upper** region is the **top horizontal dock** and the **lower** is the **editor**, **grow the upper dock** (**`+dy`** on **`horizontalToolDockHeightsPx.top`**). If the **upper** is the **editor** and the **lower** is the **bottom dock**, **grow the lower dock** (**`+dy`** on **`horizontalToolDockHeightsPx.bottom`**).

Document any intentional exception in `docs/WOP_TECHNICAL_UI.md`; default is **follow the mouse** for both axes.

## Implementation discipline

- Persist layout in **versioned or migratable** JSON (localStorage or server) so dock geometry can evolve.
- When full modular docking is not implemented yet, **do not** add layout logic that blocks future moves (e.g. unmovable wrappers, one-off CSS that only works for a single split).
- If the current build only supports a **subset** (e.g. **two** fixed slots `top` / `bottom` instead of **N** `DockStripInstance[]`), document that as **current limitation** in code comments or `docs/WOP_TECHNICAL_UI.md`, not as eternal architecture.

